484. nec cedit honori: a much vexed phrase. Briefly to clear the ground, (1) it seems better to read leonori, of which MSS. are slightly in favour, which Servius read, and which is the harder reading and less likely to be altered. (α) if honori it must be dative3 no poet could write cedit honori, cedit being common with dat., and mean honori for archaic abl. (3) cedit coming between fert and onerat must have Andromache for subject.

These things being premised nec cedit honori means literally ‘nor does she give way to honour ' i.e. nor does she fall short of honour due:
